Note:
Task #476 gate test: Match on an ADT variant-with-data must bind the stored
payload field(s) into the named pattern variables.

A variant value is laid out as: discriminator tag at offset 0, then payload
fields packed at offsets 8, 16, 24, ... The Match codegen, on a matching
PATTERN_VARIANT arm, registers each binding via codegen_add_variable, reads
that variable's stack_offset from the Variable struct (offset 8 within the
32-byte entry, i.e. variables + var_index*32 + 8), loads the payload field
from the variant, and stores it at -stack_offset(%rbp). Before #476 the
binding emission used wrong codegen-struct offsets (the count/capacity/
stack_offset trio at 12/16/24), so the bound variable received garbage
instead of the stored payload.

This suite constructs variants WITH data, matches them, and asserts the
bound payload equals what was stored.

  Case 1: single-field variant payload binds to its pattern variable
  Case 2: a different-tag single-field variant in the same Match
  Case 3: large (multi-byte) payload round-trips (full 8-byte load/store)
  Case 4: a non-zero-tag variant in a multi-variant type binds its payload
  Case 5: binding emitted with prior locals on the stack lands in the right
          slot (exercises the codegen stack_offset bookkeeping #476 fixed)

Assertions go through tests/test_utils.runa. Exits 0 with "ALL TESTS
PASSED" when every binding holds the correct payload.
:End Note

Import "tests/test_utils.runa" as T

Type Option is:
    | None
    | Some with value as Integer
End Type

Type Result is:
    | Ok with value as Integer
    | Failure with code as Integer
    | Pending
End Type

Note:
Task #490: a When pattern on a variant carrying TWO OR MORE payload fields must
bind every field. The pattern lists the field bindings comma-separated:
`When Variant with f1 as a, f2 as b:`. The parser loops over the comma-separated
field-binding pairs and appends each binding name to the clause's field_bindings
array (count at clause offset 24). Codegen loads payload field fk from the
variant at byte offset 8 + fk*8 and stores it into the fk-th binding — so the
mapping is POSITIONAL: the first listed binding receives the first payload field,
the second the second, and so on.

The #490 failure surfaced specifically with single-letter / keyword-ish binding
names such as `a` and `b`: those lex as dedicated tokens (TOKEN_A = 155, etc.),
not TOKEN_IDENTIFIER (53). The field-binding loop's strict "must be token 53"
check rejected them with "Expected binding name after 'as'". The fix accepts any
token_can_be_identifier token for both the field name and the binding name,
matching how the leading variant name and `from Module` qualifier are read.
:End Note

Type Span is:
    | Range with lo as Integer and hi as Integer
    | Empty
End Type

Type Triple is:
    | Triplet with x as Integer and y as Integer and z as Integer
End Type

Note: A binding emitted after several prior locals: proves the bound
Note: variable's stack_offset is allocated from codegen->stack_offset (offset
Note: 24) and recorded in the variable table (count at offset 16), not the
Note: confused 12/16/24 trio the #476 bug used.
Process called "tagged_sum" that takes o as Integer returns Integer:
    Let pad_a be 100
    Let pad_b be 200
    Let pad_c be 300
    Match o:
        When Some with value as v:
            Return v plus pad_a plus pad_b plus pad_c
        When None:
            Return 0
    End Match
    Return 0 minus 1
End Process

Note: Returns the payload of a Some, or -1 for None, binding the payload.
Process called "unwrap_or_neg1" that takes o as Integer returns Integer:
    Match o:
        When Some with value as v:
            Return v
        When None:
            Return 0 minus 1
    End Match
    Return 0 minus 99
End Process

Process called "main" returns Integer:
    Let results be T.create_test_results()
    T.begin_suite(results, "compiler.match_adt_binding")

    Note: Case 1: Some payload 123 must bind to v and come back as 123.
    Let o1 be Option as Some with value as 123
    Let r1 be unwrap_or_neg1(o1)
    T.assert_equal(results, "Case 1: Some payload binds", r1, 123)

    Note: Case 2: None routes to the no-data arm, returning -1.
    Let o2 be Option as None
    Let r2 be unwrap_or_neg1(o2)
    T.assert_equal(results, "Case 2: None no-data arm", r2, 0 minus 1)

    Note: Case 3: large payload round-trips through the binding (proves a
    Note: full 8-byte load/store, not a truncated/offset-confused read).
    Let o3 be Option as Some with value as 1000000007
    Let r3 be unwrap_or_neg1(o3)
    T.assert_equal(results, "Case 3: large payload binds", r3, 1000000007)

    Note: Case 4: a multi-variant Result, inline Match, single payload bound.
    Let res be Result as Failure with code as 404
    Let code be 0
    Match res:
        When Ok with value as okv:
            Set code to okv
        When Failure with code as fc:
            Set code to fc
        When Pending:
            Set code to 0 minus 5
    End Match
    T.assert_equal(results, "Case 4: Failure payload binds", code, 404)

    Note: Case 5: a binding emitted after several prior locals must land in
    Note: the correct stack slot. tagged_sum adds three pad locals before the
    Note: Match, then binds v: 17 + 100 + 200 + 300 = 617 only if v == 17.
    Let o5 be Option as Some with value as 17
    Let r5 be tagged_sum(o5)
    T.assert_equal(results, "Case 5: binding after prior locals", r5, 617)

    Note: Case 6 (#490): two-field variant, comma-separated bindings with
    Note: single-letter names `a` and `b`. Both bindings must carry the correct
    Note: payload field by position: lo (slot 0) -> a, hi (slot 1) -> b.
    Let sp be Span as Range with lo as 11 and hi as 29
    Let ra be 0
    Let rb be 0
    Match sp:
        When Range with lo as a, hi as b:
            Set ra to a
            Set rb to b
        When Empty:
            Set ra to 0 minus 1
            Set rb to 0 minus 1
    End Match
    T.assert_equal(results, "Case 6a: first field binds to a", ra, 11)
    T.assert_equal(results, "Case 6b: second field binds to b", rb, 29)

    Note: Case 7 (#490): three-field variant proves no cap on field count and
    Note: correct positional ordering across all three bindings.
    Let tr be Triple as Triplet with x as 100 and y as 200 and z as 300
    Let tx be 0
    Let ty be 0
    Let tz be 0
    Match tr:
        When Triplet with x as a, y as b, z as c:
            Set tx to a
            Set ty to b
            Set tz to c
    End Match
    T.assert_equal(results, "Case 7a: triple field 0 binds", tx, 100)
    T.assert_equal(results, "Case 7b: triple field 1 binds", ty, 200)
    T.assert_equal(results, "Case 7c: triple field 2 binds", tz, 300)

    Note: Case 8 (#490 regression guard): single-field binding with a
    Note: single-letter name `a` must still work after the predicate change.
    Let sp2 be Span as Range with lo as 41 and hi as 59
    Let only_lo be 0
    Match sp2:
        When Range with lo as a, hi as b:
            Set only_lo to a
        When Empty:
            Set only_lo to 0 minus 1
    End Match
    T.assert_equal(results, "Case 8: single-letter binding preserved", only_lo, 41)

    T.print_summary(results)
    Let ok be T.all_passed(results)
    T.destroy_test_results(results)
    If ok is equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return 1
End Process
